# .bpf Bitcasters Particle File?

# karlk: doing some normalization.
# Since we want to look things up by the ID, we use a dict at the top level,
# with the IDs as keys. (The tuple organization in .bgl files has special
# motivation: children are indicated symbolically to avoid nesting, and the
# tuple guarantees order, which is reflected in the Z-order of components.)
# It is assumed that an offset should always be converted into a Point and
# a direction into a Line starting at the origin, so the relevant data is
# omitted; it can be hard-coded.
# Particles are made into a tuple because there is no use for names for the
# individual particles - yet. We can revisit this later.
# Each animation is also given a 'name' key - this is redundant at the moment,
# but will later allow us to separate the combined-animation-particle name
# from the base animation name (although we should also think about 
# "templates"). It also helps with simplifying the code.

